Table 1
 illustrates the comparation of detection methods for TCs. In general, the traditional detection methods such as HPLC-UV, LC/MC and ELISA possess high detection accuracy, but they also have some disadvantages of requiring more complicated sample process and expensive equipment etc. Electrochemically constructed biosensors show a wide linear range, but their response times are relatively slow. Compared with the above method, fluorescence technology has significant advantages in response time, price, and real-time monitoring. In addition, the comparative of different sensors based on the fluorescence method were investigated as follows (Table 2
). The emission of R-CDs locates at the long-wave emission region (λem = 608 nm), while other CDs are limited to blue or green regions. Furthermore, the linear range and LOD of the R-CDs are superior compared with other CDs materials, which proves the potential application of R-CDs in environmental samples.
